## 6. Conditional Growth Model:

\(a\) Using your preferred model from Question 4, assess whether there is evidence that the “endogenous depression” classification is able to statistically differentiate between depression patients’ initial levels of depression.

-   The fixed effect results for model including Endog seems statistically significant(t=2.107) and positive. This indicates that endogenous patients show approximately 2.36 points higher depression scores compared with non-endogenous patients.

```{r}
conditional_model <- lmer(HamD ~ time + Endog +
                          (1 | id) +
                          (0 + time | id),
                          data = data_long,
                          REML = FALSE)

summary(conditional_model)
```

(b) Also assess whether there is evidence that this classification moderates the change in depression scores over time.

-   When adding interaction with time in the model, it seems that the interaction between time and Endog is not statistically significant(t=-0.51). This indicates that the endogenous state does not moderate the slope in depression scores over time.

```{r}
interaction_model <- lmer(HamD ~ time * Endog +
                          (1 | id) +
                          (0 + time | id),
                          data = data_long,
                          REML = FALSE)

summary(interaction_model)
```
